frameDefinitions: An Agent or Potential_hindrance keeps a Protagonist from having a State_of_affairs that they need or desire, or, despite the possibility of preventing the possession, they allow the Protagonist to have the State_of_affairs.
An Agent causes a Patient to be wet with a Liquid.
A Figure is located in the interior (the Profiled_region--see Locative_relation frame) of the Ground.
A Donor transfers a Theme from a Donor to a Recipient.
The words in this frame describe the death of a Protagonist.
An Item is in a state of dryness.
frameExamples: His parents <t>deprived</t> him of food for days on end.
The bookmark <t>inside</t> her book was torn and written on .
The machine was not switched off, but Mr. Lavelle <t>died</t> of natural causes, police said.
listRoleDefinitions: The <fen>Potential_hindrance</fen> is the force which keeps the <fen>Event</fen> from happening, or does not prevent it.
The  is the situation, state-of-affairs, or state of having a possession that the <fen>Protagonist</fen> is kept from having.
The <fen>Agent</fen> is the  person who keeps the <fen>Event</fen> from happening.
The <fen>Protagonist</fen> is the person who is kept from having the <fen>State_of_affairs</fen>.
The <fen>Time</fen> is when the <fen>Potential_hindrance</fen> keeps the <fen>Event</fen> from taking place.
The <fen>Place</fen> is where the <fen>Potential_hindrance</fen> keeps the <fen>Event</fen> from taking place.
The <fen>Agent</fen> is a volitional animate being who causes the <fen>Patient</fen> to become wet.
The <fen>Liquid</fen> is a fluid or gas that permeates or covers the <fen>Patient</fen>.  It most frequently occurs in a PP Complement headed by with.
The <fen>Patient</fen> takes up the <fen>Liquid</fen> through its pores or has the <fen>Liquid</fen> covering its surface.
An animate or inanimate entity, a force, or event that produces the state of wetness.
This role identifies the <fen>Time</fen> when the <fen>Agent</fen> wets the <fen>Patient</fen>.
This role identifies the <fen>Place</fen> where the <fen>Agent</fen> wets the <fen>Patient</fen>.
The <fen>Figure</fen> is the entity located with respect to the <fen>Ground</fen>.
The <fen>Ground</fen> is the area that the <fen>Figure</fen> is located in.
The area or zone interior to the <fen>Ground</fen>.  This role excludes <fen>Figure</fen> and is only used in particular constructions such as the following:
The time during which the <fen>Figure</fen> was located in the <fen>Ground</fen>.
The person that begins in possession of the <fen>Theme</fen> and causes it to be in the possession of the <fen>Recipient</fen> .
The entity that ends up in possession of the <fen>Theme</fen>.
The object that changes ownership.
The <fen>Time</fen> is when the <fen>Donor</fen> gives the <fen>Theme</fen> to the <fen>Recipient</fen>.
The <fen>Place</fen> where the <fen>Donor</fen> gives the <fen>Theme</fen> to the <fen>Recipient</fen>.
The role <fen>Protagonist</fen> is the being or entity that dies.  With verbs in this frame, the <fen>Protagonist</fen> is the External Argument.
The role <fen>Time</fen> denotes when the dying or killing occurs.
The role <fen>Place</fen> indicates where the death takes place.
The <fen>Item</fen> exists in a state of dryness.
listRoleExamples: <fex>Israeli law</fex> effectively deprived the owners of their homes and lands.
Their parents denied them <fex>a brand new car</fex> upon their sweet 16.
<fex>The uncaring King Frank</fex> often starves his citizens of tax relief.
<fex>Hannah</fex> drenched the cat with anti-flea ointment.
Inside the cupboard was <fex>a good place to hide</fex> .
Your father passed away <fex>about four minutes ago</fex>.
Your father passed away <fex>in his hospital bed</fex>.
